  fiber: 5 g
  sodium: 1890 mg
time required: 20 minutes
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/shrimp-and-edamame-stir-fry-with-gochujang-aioli-6787f732b5302a11d0e4836e
---

In a small #pot{}, combine @jasmine rice{3/4%cup}, @water{1 1/4%cups} (2 1⁄4 cups for 4 servings), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, wash and dry produce.

Trim and quarter @zucchini{1} lengthwise; slice crosswise into 1⁄4-inch-thick quarter-moons. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Rinse @shrimp{10%oz} under cold water, then pat dry with paper towels. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add shrimp; season with salt and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until shrimp are opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add zucchini, @edamame{4%oz}, scallion whites, and @red cabbage and carrot mix{4%oz}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are browned and tender, ~{3-5%minutes}. Turn off heat.

Use pan used for shrimp here.

Meanwhile, in a small #bowl{}, combine @gochujang aioli{1} with water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Stir @sweet soy glaze{4%tbsp}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%oz}, and water 2 TBSP (4 TBSP for 4 servings) into pan with stir-fry; stir to coat. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, stir in a splash of water.

Stir in shrimp along with sweet soy glaze, chili sauce, and water.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}.

Divide rice between shallow #bowls{}. Top with edamame stir-fry. Drizzle with as much gochujang aioli as you like. Sprinkle with @sesame seeds{1%tbsp} and scallion greens. Serve.

> Shellfish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.